Abstract
Pilgrimage tourism in India draws millions of devotees annually to temple towns such as Tirupati, Varanasi, Shirdi, Vaishno Devi, and Rameswaram. Despite the scale of this movement, most pilgrims still rely on fragmented information sources — separate transport booking portals, third-party darshan slot websites, printed guides, and word-of-mouth advice — to plan a single visit. This fragmentation results in avoidable delays, missed darshan slots, uninformed travel choices, and a stressful experience for a journey that is, for most visitors, deeply personal and time-constrained.
DarshanEase is a full-stack web application designed to consolidate the temple visit planning experience into a single, coherent platform. Built using the MERN-oriented stack — React with Vite on the client and Node.js with Express and MongoDB on the server — the application allows a user to search for temples, view essential visit information, plan a multi-leg journey (covering transport and darshan scheduling), and manage bookings from an authenticated personal dashboard. The system further introduces a conversational assistant to help users obtain temple- and travel-related guidance in natural language, and provides distinct interfaces for pilgrims, temple/tour organizers, and administrators.
This report documents the complete engineering lifecycle of DarshanEase: the motivation and problem statement, requirement analysis, system and database design, the technology choices and their justification, the module-wise implementation of the frontend and backend, the REST API surface exposed by the server, and the testing strategy used to validate functional correctness. The report also discusses the current limitations of the implementation and proposes a roadmap of future enhancements, including deeper AI-assisted itinerary generation, real-time slot availability integration, and multilingual support.
The objective of this documentation is to present an accurate, verifiable account of the system as implemented in the project repository, structured in the format prescribed by the SmartBridge project submission guidelines, so that it may serve both as an academic record and as a technical reference for future maintenance or extension of the platform.
