Technology Stack (Explain why each technology was selected)
The technology choices for DarshanEase, as reflected in the project repository's client and server dependencies, were driven by the need for rapid full-stack development in a single language, a flexible data model suited to evolving trip-planning data, and rich client-side visualization for maps and interactive elements.
Layer	Technology	Reason for Selection
Frontend framework	React	Component-based architecture suits a UI composed of reusable elements (temple cards, booking forms, dashboard widgets) and has the largest ecosystem of supporting libraries.
Build tool	Vite	Significantly faster development server start-up and hot module replacement compared to older bundlers, improving iteration speed during development.
Styling	Tailwind CSS / Bootstrap (utility and component styling)	Enables rapid, consistent UI styling without hand-writing large volumes of custom CSS.
Routing	React Router	Provides declarative, client-side routing needed for a single-page application with distinct views (home, temple detail, planner, dashboard, auth).
State management	React Context API	Sufficient for the scale of shared state required (authentication/session state) without the overhead of a larger state-management library.
3D / animated visuals	Three.js with @react-three/fiber and @react-three/drei	Allows immersive, animated visual elements on marketing/landing sections to differentiate the product experience.
Motion / transitions	Framer Motion, React Spring	Provide smooth, declarative UI animations for a polished, modern interface.
Maps	Leaflet / React-Leaflet	A lightweight, open-source mapping library well suited to rendering temple locations without a paid mapping API dependency.
Data visualization	Recharts	Used to render any dashboard-style charts (e.g., summary statistics) with a React-native charting API.
HTTP client	Axios	Simplifies making authenticated REST calls from the client to the Express API, including attaching JWT headers.
Backend runtime	Node.js	Enables JavaScript on the server, matching the client language and simplifying full-stack development.
Backend framework	Express.js	A minimal, unopinionated framework for defining REST routes, middleware, and controllers.
Database	MongoDB	A document-oriented database whose flexible schema is well suited to nested, evolving structures such as journey plans and booking records.
ODM	Mongoose	Provides schema definition, validation, and a convenient query API over MongoDB from within the Node.js server.
File uploads	Multer	Handles multipart form data for any image or document upload functionality within the platform.
Cross-origin support	CORS	Allows the separately-hosted React client to communicate with the Express API during development and production.
Authentication	JSON Web Tokens (JWT)	Provides stateless, scalable authentication without requiring server-side session storage.
Table 5: Technology stack used in DarshanEase and the rationale for each choice.
