Module Description
DarshanEase is organized into five functional modules, each corresponding to a coherent slice of the user journey: the User Module, the Admin Module, the Authentication Module, the Booking Module, the Journey Planning Module, and the AI Chatbot Module. Each module spans both the client (React components/pages) and the server (routes, controllers, models) and is described individually in the sections that follow.
Module	Primary Responsibility	Key Actors
User Module	Profile display, dashboard, booking history.	User
Admin Module	Platform oversight: user, temple, and booking management.	Administrator / Organizer
Authentication Module	Registration, login, session/token management.	User, Organizer, Admin
Booking Module	Creation, storage, and retrieval of booking records.	User
Journey Planning Module	Assembling a travel and darshan plan for a selected temple.	User
AI Chatbot Module	Natural-language assistance for temple/travel queries.	User
Table 6: Summary of DarshanEase functional modules.
User Module
The User Module governs the pilgrim-facing experience once a visitor has authenticated. On the client, this module is realized as a set of page-level React components — a landing/home page presenting featured temples, a temple directory/search view, a temple detail view with an embedded map, and a personal dashboard summarizing the user's bookings and profile information.
Responsibilities
•Render the temple directory and support search/filtering of temples.
•Display individual temple detail pages, combining textual information with an interactive map view.
•Present the user's personal dashboard, listing their past and upcoming bookings.
•Allow the user to initiate the Journey Planning workflow from a temple's detail page.
•Surface the chatbot entry point for on-demand assistance.
Server-Side Support
The User Module is supported on the backend primarily by the temple-listing endpoints (to populate the directory and detail views) and the booking-retrieval endpoint (to populate the dashboard). These endpoints are described in full in the API Documentation section of this report.
Admin Module
The Admin Module provides the oversight interface required to keep the platform's temple directory and booking records accurate and orderly. Where the User Module is oriented around discovery and planning, the Admin Module is oriented around content and data management.
Responsibilities
•Manage the master list of temples available to users, including adding, updating, or removing temple records.
•Review booking activity across users for operational oversight.
•Support the Organizer role in maintaining temple- or tour-specific content relevant to their scope of responsibility.
•Provide a controlled entry point distinct from the general user interface, protected by role-aware authentication.
Design Rationale
Separating administrative capability from the pilgrim-facing interface keeps the primary user experience uncluttered while still allowing the data that underpins it (the temple directory in particular) to be curated and kept current.
Authentication Module
The Authentication Module is the security backbone of DarshanEase: every booking, dashboard view, and profile action is scoped to an authenticated identity, and the module is responsible for establishing and verifying that identity on every relevant request.
Registration and Login Flow
A new user registers with a name, email address, and password through a client-side registration form. On the server, the corresponding controller validates the submitted fields, hashes the password (a standard and necessary practice to avoid storing credentials in plain text), and persists a new User document. On login, the submitted email and password are checked against the stored (hashed) credential; on success, the server issues a signed JSON Web Token that encodes the user's identity and is returned to the client.
Session Handling on the Client
The issued token is stored on the client (for example, in browser storage or in-memory application state managed through the Context API) and attached to the Authorization header of subsequent API requests that require an authenticated identity, such as booking creation or dashboard retrieval.
Server-Side Protection
Protected Express routes are wrapped with an authentication middleware function that verifies the JWT signature and expiry before allowing the request to reach its controller. If verification fails, the middleware short-circuits the request with an unauthorized response rather than allowing it to reach any data-access logic — ensuring that booking and profile data can never be read or modified without a valid token.
Step	Client Action	Server Action
1	Submit registration form	Validate input, hash password, create User document
2	Submit login form	Validate credentials, issue signed JWT
3	Store token, attach to future requests	Verify JWT via middleware on protected routes
4	Access dashboard / create booking	Resolve authenticated user ID from token, execute controller logic
Table 7: Authentication flow between client and server in DarshanEase.
Booking Module
The Booking Module is responsible for turning a planned visit into a persisted record associated with the authenticated user, and for surfacing that record back to the user on demand.
Creation Flow
Once a user finalizes a plan in the Journey Planning Module, the client submits a booking request containing the relevant temple reference, the user's chosen travel/darshan details, and any other itinerary fields captured during planning. The server-side booking controller confirms the request is authenticated, associates the booking with the resolved user ID, and writes a new Booking document to MongoDB.
Retrieval Flow
The user's dashboard retrieves their booking history through an endpoint that queries the Booking collection filtered by the authenticated user's ID, returning the set of bookings in a format the client can render as a list of trip summaries.
Design Considerations
•Every booking write and read operation is gated by the Authentication Module, ensuring bookings can only be created or viewed by their owner.
•The Booking model references the Temple collection so that a booking can always be traced back to full temple details without duplicating that data on every booking document.
•Because MongoDB's schema is flexible, the Booking model can accommodate itinerary details of varying shape (e.g., single-temple versus multi-leg trips) without requiring a rigid, pre-declared column set as would be needed in a relational database.
Journey Planning Module
The Journey Planning Module is the workflow through which a user converts an interest in visiting a temple into a concrete plan — combining transport considerations with darshan scheduling — before it is committed as a booking.
Workflow
•The user selects a temple from the directory or detail page, carrying the temple's identity into the planner.
•The user specifies travel-related preferences relevant to reaching the temple town (for example, mode of travel and approximate travel dates).
•The user specifies darshan-related preferences (for example, preferred visit date/time window), where such information is available for the selected temple.
•The planner presents a consolidated view of these choices for the user to review before proceeding to booking.
•On confirmation, the plan is handed off to the Booking Module for persistence.
Client-Side Composition
On the client, the planner is implemented as a multi-step or multi-section form component that collects the fields above, using controlled form inputs and client-side validation before submission. Map integration (via Leaflet/React-Leaflet) is used within this module to give the user spatial context for the temple's location relative to transport hubs.
AI Chatbot Module (if implemented)
DarshanEase includes an AI-assisted conversational interface intended to let users ask natural-language questions about temples and journey planning rather than navigating structured menus for every query. On the client, this is presented as a chat widget accessible from the main application shell.
Purpose
The chatbot module reduces the friction of finding contextual information (such as temple etiquette, general visiting guidance, or clarification about the planning workflow) by allowing the user to phrase a question conversationally instead of searching through static pages.
Interaction Model
The user submits a natural-language message through the chat widget; the message is sent to a backend endpoint responsible for producing a response, which is then rendered back into the conversation thread on the client. The chat history is maintained client-side for the duration of the session, giving the interaction a continuous, conversational feel.
Verification Note
The presence of a conversational assistant is confirmed by the project's stated feature set. The precise backend mechanism used to generate responses (a rules/template-based responder versus an external language-model API call) could not be independently confirmed from the metadata accessible in this analysis; this should be verified against the actual controller implementation before being cited in a formal evaluation as a specific technique.
Database Design
DarshanEase uses MongoDB as its primary data store, accessed from the Express server through Mongoose schemas. The document model was chosen because the core domain objects — a temple profile, a user account, and a booking/itinerary record — are naturally hierarchical and vary in shape (for instance, not every temple will have identical metadata fields, and a booking's itinerary detail can differ from trip to trip). A document database avoids the schema-migration overhead a relational model would impose for this kind of variability, while Mongoose still provides validation at the application layer.
The design centres on three primary collections — Users, Temples, and Bookings — related to one another through reference fields (ObjectId references) rather than embedding, which keeps each collection independently queryable and avoids unbounded document growth (for example, a temple with thousands of bookings would not need to store them all inline).
ER Diagram
  +----------------+          +----------------+          +----------------+
  |     USER       |          |    BOOKING      |          |    TEMPLE      |
  +----------------+          +----------------+          +----------------+
  | _id            |<---1---N-| userId (FK)    |-N---1--->| _id            |
  | name           |          | _id            |          | name           |
  | email (unique)  |          | temple Id (FK) |          | location        |
  | password (hash) |          | travelDetails   |          | description     |
  | role            |          | darshanDetails  |          | timings         |
  | createdAt       |          | status          |          | latitude/long   |
  +----------------+          | createdAt       |          | imageUrl        |
                              +----------------+          +----------------+
Figure 9: Entity-Relationship diagram of the DarshanEase data model.
Each User may have zero or many Bookings (a one-to-many relationship), and each Booking references exactly one Temple, while a Temple may be referenced by many Bookings (a one-to-many relationship in the opposite direction). This yields the classic many-to-many relationship between Users and Temples, mediated through the Booking collection, which additionally carries the itinerary-specific data (travel details, darshan details, and status) for each individual visit plan.
Database Collections/Tables
Users Collection
Field	Type	Description
_id	ObjectId	Primary key, auto-generated by MongoDB.
name	String	Full name of the registered user.
email	String (unique)	Login identifier; enforced unique at the schema level.
password	String (hashed)	Hashed password credential; never stored in plain text.
role	String (enum)	Distinguishes user / organizer / admin for role-based access.
createdAt	Date	Timestamp of account creation.
Table 8: Users collection schema.
Temples Collection
Field	Type	Description
_id	ObjectId	Primary key, auto-generated by MongoDB.
name	String	Name of the temple.
location	String	Human-readable location (town/state).
latitude / longitude	Number	Geographic coordinates used for map rendering.
description	String	Descriptive information about the temple.
timings	String	Visiting/darshan hours.
imageUrl	String	Reference to a representative image asset.
Table 9: Temples collection schema.
Bookings Collection
Field	Type	Description
_id	ObjectId	Primary key, auto-generated by MongoDB.
userId	ObjectId (ref: User)	Reference to the user who created the booking.
templeId	ObjectId (ref: Temple)	Reference to the temple being visited.
travelDetails	Object	Travel-related plan fields captured from the Journey Planning Module.
darshanDetails	Object	Darshan scheduling fields captured from the Journey Planning Module.
status	String (enum)	Current state of the booking (e.g., pending / confirmed / completed).
createdAt	Date	Timestamp of booking creation.
Table 10: Bookings collection schema.
Verification note: field-level names above reflect the data described by the platform's feature set (user identity, temple metadata, and a booking that links the two together with travel/darshan detail and status). Exact field names in the live Mongoose schema files could not be confirmed due to the repository access limitation noted in the Folder Structure section, and should be cross-checked against models/User.js, models/Temple.js, and models/Booking.js before this table is treated as a literal schema export.
API Documentation
The Express server exposes a REST API under the /api namespace. Endpoints are grouped into three resource areas corresponding to the Authentication, Temple, and Booking modules. All request and response bodies use JSON, and protected endpoints require a valid JWT supplied in the Authorization header using the Bearer scheme.
Method	Endpoint	Description	Auth Required
POST	/api/auth/register	Register a new user account.	No
POST	/api/auth/login	Authenticate a user and issue a JWT.	No
GET	/api/temples	Retrieve the list of all temples.	No
GET	/api/temples/:id	Retrieve details for a single temple by ID.	No
POST	/api/bookings	Create a new booking for the authenticated user.	Yes
GET	/api/bookings/user	Retrieve the booking history of the authenticated user.	Yes
Table 11: Core REST API endpoints exposed by the DarshanEase backend.
This endpoint set corresponds to the routes documented in the project repository. Additional administrative or organizer-facing endpoints (for temple content management, for instance) are implied by the Admin Module described earlier but were not independently enumerated in the accessible repository metadata; they should be confirmed against the routes/ directory of the backend before being cited as an exhaustive API reference.
