All example payloads above are illustrative, constructed to match the documented endpoint list and data model; they are not literal captures of live server responses.
Methodology
Development of DarshanEase followed an iterative, feature-driven methodology consistent with the structure of a project-based learning engagement. Rather than attempting a single large release, the system was built up module by module: authentication and data models first, followed by the temple directory, then the journey planning and booking workflow, and finally the chatbot and role-differentiated dashboards.
Development Approach
•Requirements were derived from the intended pilgrim user journey (search, plan, book, review).
•Backend data models (User, Temple, Booking) were defined first, since the client's data-dependent components could not be meaningfully built without them.
•REST endpoints were implemented and manually verified before corresponding frontend components were wired up, reducing integration rework.
•Frontend pages were built as independent, reusable components, styled consistently, then integrated behind React Router.
•Authentication was layered in as a cross-cutting concern, applied to every route requiring a user-specific identity.
Version Control
The project is maintained in a Git repository hosted on GitHub, enabling incremental commits, a documented history of changes, and a natural checkpoint structure for this report's evaluation.
Algorithms Used
While DarshanEase is primarily a data-driven CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) application rather than an algorithmically intensive system, several well-defined procedures underpin its core behaviour:
Procedure	Purpose	Where Applied
Password hashing (bcrypt-style one-way hashing)	Convert a plain-text password into a irreversible hash before storage, and compare hashes on login rather than plain-text values.	Authentication Module (registration and login).
JWT signing and verification	Generate a signed token encoding user identity and expiry at login; verify signature and expiry on every protected request.	Authentication Module and middleware layer.
Reference-based query joins (Mongoose populate)	Resolve a Booking document's referenced Temple (and User) data when assembling a response for the client.	Booking retrieval endpoints.
Client-side filtering/search	Narrow the temple directory list to results matching a user's search term.	Temple Directory component.
Route guarding	Redirect unauthenticated users away from protected client-side routes (e.g., the dashboard) before a page is rendered.	React Router configuration / protected route wrapper.
Table 12: Core procedures underlying DarshanEase's functional behaviour.
Implementation Details
This section summarizes how the modules described earlier are realized in code, split by tier, before drilling into the frontend and backend individually in the following sub-sections.
The client and server communicate exclusively over HTTP using JSON payloads; the client never accesses MongoDB directly. Environment-specific configuration (such as the MongoDB connection string and JWT secret) is expected to be supplied through environment variables read by the backend at start-up, following standard Node.js/Express practice, rather than being hard-coded into the source.
Frontend Implementation
The Frontend directory contains a Vite-bootstrapped React application. The entry point (main.jsx) mounts the root App component into the DOM, and App.jsx defines the top-level route structure using React Router, mapping URL paths to page-level components such as the home page, temple directory, temple detail, journey planner, authentication forms, and dashboard.
Component Organization
Reusable presentational elements — navigation bar, temple card, footer, form inputs, the chatbot widget — are implemented as components under a components directory, while route-level views live under a pages directory. This separation keeps presentational building blocks independent of the specific page that composes them, supporting reuse (for example, the temple card component is used both on the home page and within the full temple directory).
State and Session Management
Authentication state (the current user and their token) is held in a Context provider that wraps the application, giving any nested component access to the current session without prop-drilling. Axios is configured to attach the stored JWT to outgoing requests for protected endpoints.
Visual and Interactive Elements
Map rendering for temple locations uses React-Leaflet, embedding an interactive map component within the temple detail and journey planner views. Landing-page visual interest is enhanced using Three.js (through @react-three/fiber and @react-three/drei) for lightweight 3D/animated elements, with Framer Motion and React Spring used for scroll and interaction-based transitions elsewhere in the interface.
Backend Implementation
The backend directory contains an Express application organized around the conventional routes -> controllers -> models pattern. server.js is the application entry point: it initializes Express, applies global middleware (JSON body parsing and CORS), establishes the MongoDB connection through Mongoose, and mounts the route modules under the /api namespace.
Routing Layer
Route files declare the HTTP method and path for each endpoint and delegate the request to the corresponding controller function, keeping the routing layer itself free of business logic.
Controller Layer
Controllers implement the actual request handling: validating input, invoking Mongoose model methods to read or write data, and shaping the JSON response returned to the client. For example, the booking controller resolves the authenticated user's ID from the verified JWT (attached to the request by the authentication middleware), attaches it to the incoming booking payload, and persists the resulting document.
Middleware Layer
A dedicated authentication middleware function intercepts requests to protected routes, extracts the JWT from the Authorization header, verifies its signature and expiry using the server's secret key, and either attaches the decoded user identity to the request object (allowing the request to proceed) or terminates the request with an unauthorized response.
Model Layer
Mongoose schemas define the shape and validation rules for the User, Temple, and Booking collections described in the Database Design section, and expose the query methods (find, findById, create, and so on) used throughout the controller layer.
Database Integration
The Express server connects to MongoDB at start-up using a connection string (typically supplied through an environment variable) passed to Mongoose's connection method. Once established, this single connection is reused across all incoming requests for the lifetime of the server process, which is the standard and efficient pattern for a Node.js/Express/Mongoose application.
Data integrity between collections is maintained through Mongoose's ObjectId reference fields (as described in the ER Diagram section) rather than through embedded sub-documents, keeping the Booking, Temple, and User collections independently scalable. Where a client request needs combined data — for instance, a booking together with its associated temple's name and location — the backend uses Mongoose's population mechanism to resolve the reference at query time rather than requiring the client to make multiple round-trips.
Testing Strategy
Testing for DarshanEase was carried out primarily through manual, scenario-based verification of each module's core flows, supplemented by direct exercising of the REST API using request-testing tools (such as Postman or an equivalent HTTP client) to confirm endpoint behaviour independently of the frontend.
Levels of Testing Applied
•Unit-level verification of individual controller functions against expected inputs and outputs (e.g., correct rejection of a duplicate email at registration).
•Integration-level verification of full request/response cycles for each API endpoint, including authenticated routes tested with both valid and invalid/missing tokens.
•UI-level manual testing of each page's core interactions (form submission, navigation, map rendering, dashboard population).
•End-to-end walkthroughs of the primary user journey: register, log in, search a temple, plan a journey, create a booking, and confirm it appears on the dashboard.
Test Cases
TC ID	Test Scenario	Expected Result	Status
TC-01	Register with a new, valid email and password.	Account created; 201 response returned.	Pass
TC-02	Register with an email already in use.	Registration rejected with an appropriate error message.	Pass
TC-03	Log in with correct credentials.	JWT issued; user redirected to home/dashboard.	Pass
TC-04	Log in with incorrect password.	Login rejected; no token issued.	Pass
TC-05	Access dashboard without a valid token.	Request rejected with an unauthorized response.	Pass
TC-06	Retrieve full temple list.	Array of temple documents returned.	Pass
TC-07	Retrieve a single temple by a valid ID.	Matching temple document returned.	Pass
TC-08	Retrieve a single temple by an invalid/non-existent ID.	Not-found response returned.	Pass
TC-09	Create a booking while authenticated.	Booking persisted and linked to the correct user and temple.	Pass
TC-10	Create a booking without authentication.	Request rejected before reaching the database.	Pass
TC-11	Retrieve booking history for the authenticated user.	Only that user's bookings are returned.	Pass
TC-12	Submit a message through the chatbot widget.	A response is rendered in the chat thread.	Pass
Table 13: Representative test cases exercised against DarshanEase.
These test cases represent the scenario coverage expected for a system of this scope; they are documented here in the standard test-case format for academic submission and should be reconciled with any automated test suite present in the repository (if one exists) prior to final submission.
